      "content": "The view that universal systems are \"inefficient\" often dissolves when one defines efficiency not by raw spending volume, but by cost-effectiveness relative to health outcomes, which typically favors nations like Canada or the UK. However, most systems balance high costs against high equity, meaning the debate isn't just about facts but who prioritizes healthspan versus healthcare spending power. Acknowledging that cost isn't the only metric of success allows both sides to exist in a productive dialogue rather than a zero-sum confrontation.",
